WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.360
or sewage treatment plants, or nuclear reactors.

00:04.360 --> 00:07.680
All of these major pieces of expensive hardware

00:07.680 --> 00:10.680
are run by what are called industrial control systems.

00:10.680 --> 00:26.320
And this module, we're going to talk about industrial control systems

00:26.320 --> 00:28.720
and internet of things.

00:28.720 --> 00:43.520
Let's start with industrial control systems.

00:43.520 --> 00:46.400
In this module, we're going to talk about industrial control systems

00:46.400 --> 00:48.800
and internet of things.

00:48.800 --> 00:51.480
Let's start with industrial control systems.

00:51.480 --> 00:55.080
And a definition, what are industrial control systems?

00:55.080 --> 00:58.920
Well, industrial control systems are the hardware and the software

00:58.920 --> 01:01.600
that control big expensive hardware.

01:01.600 --> 01:04.600
So think manufacturing facilities with all those raw watts

01:04.600 --> 01:07.920
that are building cars or iPhones.

01:07.920 --> 01:11.600
Or think of water treatment plants, or sewage treatment plants,

01:11.600 --> 01:14.520
or nuclear reactors.

01:14.520 --> 01:17.840
All of these major pieces of expensive hardware

01:17.840 --> 01:22.160
are run by what are called industrial control systems.

01:22.160 --> 01:26.240
So given that these industrial control systems control very expensive

01:26.240 --> 01:30.440
and often very delicate and potentially catastrophic systems

01:30.440 --> 01:34.040
if they were to fail, like nuclear power plants or water treatment plants,

01:34.040 --> 01:38.360
these systems have to be very secure and very reliable.

01:38.360 --> 01:41.320
There's three major types of industrial control systems

01:41.320 --> 01:42.800
that you need to know both for the examine.

01:42.800 --> 01:44.480
You do not have to be an expert on these,

01:44.480 --> 01:47.280
but you should recognize that these systems,

01:47.280 --> 01:48.600
you're the names of these systems,

01:48.600 --> 01:51.160
are examples of industrial control systems.

01:51.160 --> 01:53.280
The most common are SCADA systems.

01:53.280 --> 01:57.080
You've also got DCS and PLC systems.

01:57.080 --> 01:58.480
And actually remember for the exam,

01:58.480 --> 02:01.360
you do not have to memorize all these acronyms.

02:01.360 --> 02:04.160
There'll be a little window that you can button that you can click

02:04.160 --> 02:07.560
that will show you a pop-up window that contains all sorts of acronyms

02:07.560 --> 02:09.480
and what they actually stand for.

02:09.480 --> 02:11.560
So you don't have to memorize the exact wording of these things

02:11.560 --> 02:14.000
and you won't get definitional type questions on that.

02:14.000 --> 02:17.880
So be aware SCADA, DCS and PLC.

02:17.880 --> 02:20.720
These are very common types of industrial control systems.

02:22.320 --> 02:25.760
Now, the big risk that we have with industrial control systems

02:25.760 --> 02:27.160
is that these are very expensive,

02:27.160 --> 02:29.720
very important systems that are controlling,

02:29.720 --> 02:33.200
often extremely expensive, very delicate systems.

02:33.200 --> 02:36.360
And the big security risk is that the hardware,

02:36.360 --> 02:38.480
the software that these SCADA systems are running around

02:38.480 --> 02:40.920
or these industrial control systems are running on

02:40.920 --> 02:43.200
is often very outdated.

02:43.200 --> 02:46.360
It's not uncommon to come across industrial control systems

02:46.360 --> 02:48.600
that are still running on like Windows NT.

02:48.600 --> 02:49.880
It's crazy sometimes.

02:50.880 --> 02:53.160
So let's start with a question.

02:53.160 --> 02:55.720
Why are some of these such critical systems running

02:55.720 --> 02:59.080
on such old antiquated hardware and software?

02:59.080 --> 03:02.720
And the answer is these are very, very critical systems

03:02.720 --> 03:04.720
that are often highly customized.

03:04.720 --> 03:07.120
So it's often very difficult to upgrade

03:07.120 --> 03:09.480
the underlying operating system and hardware.

03:09.480 --> 03:13.280
And a lot of these big facilities very much run by the philosophy

03:13.880 --> 03:16.600
of if it ain't broken, don't fix it.

03:16.600 --> 03:19.000
Because you do not want to cause an outage

03:19.000 --> 03:21.000
or cause these systems to malfunction.

03:22.120 --> 03:25.040
So in many cases, we have very outdated,

03:25.040 --> 03:28.800
very insecure hardware and underlying operating systems

03:28.800 --> 03:31.800
that these industrial control systems are running on top of.

03:31.800 --> 03:35.080
And yet these are extremely critical systems.

03:35.080 --> 03:36.440
So how do we protect them?

03:36.440 --> 03:39.760
How do we reduce the risk related to these systems?

03:39.760 --> 03:41.680
The number one best way, and this is what you should remember

03:41.680 --> 03:44.040
is the exam, air gap.

03:44.040 --> 03:47.360
So air gaping is the concept that the industrial control system,

03:47.360 --> 03:48.800
the network that it's on,

03:48.800 --> 03:52.160
should absolutely not be connected to the rest

03:52.160 --> 03:55.080
of the corporate network and especially the internet.

03:55.080 --> 03:56.840
There should be a physical air gap,

03:56.840 --> 03:59.880
literally no connection between the industrial control system

03:59.880 --> 04:03.080
network and the rest of the corporate network

04:03.080 --> 04:04.240
and especially the internet.

04:04.240 --> 04:06.440
So remember air gaping is one of the best ways

04:06.440 --> 04:09.120
of reducing the risk of industrial control systems.

04:10.000 --> 04:13.080
Now, let's talk about the internet of things.

04:13.080 --> 04:14.720
What is the internet of things?

04:14.720 --> 04:16.840
Well, it's all sorts of devices

04:16.840 --> 04:20.040
that have been given the ability to connect to the internet

04:20.040 --> 04:22.280
that probably shouldn't be connected to the internet,

04:22.280 --> 04:24.880
like your fridge and your stove and your dishwasher

04:24.880 --> 04:25.960
and your light bulb.

04:27.840 --> 04:30.760
So here's what's really led to this.

04:30.760 --> 04:33.400
The ability to make a little computer chip,

04:33.400 --> 04:35.440
basically a little mini computer

04:35.440 --> 04:38.800
that has Wi-Fi capabilities and can connect to the internet

04:38.800 --> 04:40.640
has become unbelievably cheap.

04:40.640 --> 04:43.760
We can make these things for a couple of bucks.

04:43.760 --> 04:46.360
And as a result, it's become extraordinarily cheap

04:46.360 --> 04:49.720
to put these capabilities into all sorts of devices.

04:49.720 --> 04:51.920
And that's exactly what's happening.

04:51.920 --> 04:54.200
And there's a few big risks here.

04:54.200 --> 04:58.760
One, most of these internet of things chips

04:58.760 --> 05:03.600
are made by big OEM, original equipment manufacturers.

05:03.600 --> 05:05.360
They were, there's just a few manufacturers

05:05.360 --> 05:07.800
that make the vast majority of these

05:07.800 --> 05:09.480
internet of things little computers

05:09.480 --> 05:11.320
that enable this capability.

05:11.320 --> 05:15.000
And security is not typically their top priority.

05:15.000 --> 05:18.560
It's to make these things to the lowest possible dollar.

05:18.560 --> 05:22.480
And so a lot of the internet of things devices out there

05:22.480 --> 05:24.800
are wildly insecure.

05:24.800 --> 05:26.760
They have big vulnerabilities in them.

05:26.760 --> 05:30.360
And a lot of them are actually very difficult to patch.

05:30.360 --> 05:32.040
And you combine that with the fact that

05:32.040 --> 05:33.320
when you install these capabilities

05:33.320 --> 05:35.160
in a lot of devices like a fridge or a stove,

05:35.160 --> 05:38.160
I mean, who thinks to patch their fridge?

05:38.160 --> 05:40.920
It's just, it's not something that people think about.

05:40.920 --> 05:43.240
You plug this device in, you connect it to the internet,

05:43.240 --> 05:44.800
and then you forget that it's there.

05:44.800 --> 05:47.480
You forget it's connected to the internet.

05:47.480 --> 05:49.000
And that leads to the next big risk.

05:49.000 --> 05:52.080
And that is that these internet of things devices

05:52.080 --> 05:57.280
can provide a really easy attack platform for a hacker.

05:57.280 --> 05:59.920
So I'll give you an example of this.

05:59.920 --> 06:02.920
The largest ever denial of service attack,

06:02.920 --> 06:06.720
the largest ever denial of service attack in history,

06:06.720 --> 06:10.440
originated from security cameras.

06:10.440 --> 06:13.760
So someone discovered a vulnerability in security cameras,

06:13.760 --> 06:15.840
installed some malware that allowed them

06:15.840 --> 06:18.440
to remotely control these security cameras,

06:18.440 --> 06:21.840
created a giant botnet essentially of these security cameras,

06:21.840 --> 06:24.800
and then perpetrated the largest denial of service attack

06:24.800 --> 06:27.800
in history from security cameras.

06:27.800 --> 06:30.520
That's pretty ironic.

06:30.520 --> 06:34.480
And that highlights the risk with these systems.

06:34.480 --> 06:36.560
We don't realize they're connected to the internet,

06:36.560 --> 06:38.880
and we don't think to patch them.

06:38.880 --> 06:41.400
And because we've put them often deep inside of our corporate

06:41.400 --> 06:44.040
networks or inside of our personal networks,

06:44.040 --> 06:45.640
we don't think of the fact that someone

06:45.640 --> 06:47.840
may be able to remotely connect to this device,

06:47.840 --> 06:52.880
compromise the device, and now they're inside of our environment.

06:52.880 --> 06:56.640
So how do we reduce the risk of internet of things devices?

06:56.640 --> 06:58.480
How do we deal with this problem?

06:58.480 --> 07:01.200
Well, it's best to think of internet of things devices

07:01.200 --> 07:04.200
as a computer system, because that's literally what they are.

07:04.200 --> 07:07.360
So all the same principles that you'd apply to protecting

07:07.360 --> 07:10.320
any computer system apply to internet of things devices.

07:10.320 --> 07:11.600
You need to make sure they're patched.

07:11.600 --> 07:13.320
You need to make sure they're configured properly

07:13.320 --> 07:16.000
that they have proper authentication in place.

07:16.000 --> 07:18.200
And because it's often difficult to do all of that

07:18.200 --> 07:19.480
with a lot of these devices,

07:19.480 --> 07:21.520
network segmentation is really important.

07:21.520 --> 07:23.720
Put these things on their own network segment.

07:23.720 --> 07:26.200
If they truly do need to connect to the internet,

07:26.200 --> 07:28.040
put them off in some network where that's

07:28.080 --> 07:31.080
all that they can connect to, or even better yet,

07:31.080 --> 07:33.360
don't connect them to any internet.

07:33.360 --> 07:34.960
So that's internet of things.

